{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c49d256-1809-4a5b-92a4-6b8996b45c7a","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's security frameworks (`Security.framework`) **do not support DSA**. In earlier .NET versions on macOS, DSA worked via an **OpenSSL shim** that .NET shipped or relied on from Homebrew. In .NET 11, Microsoft completed the removal of the OpenSSL backend on macOS for legacy algorithms, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**.\n\nThis only affects macOS — Windows uses CNG (which supports DSA) and Linux uses the system OpenSSL.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have three options, depending on your constraints:\n\n### Option 1 — Migrate away from DSA (preferred)\nDSA is considered legacy. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, which are supported on all platforms.\n\n### Option 2 — Use BouncyCastle for verification\nIf you must verify existing DSA signatures, use **BouncyCastle**, which is a managed implementation with no OS dependency:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Load your DSA public key parameters and create a verifier\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, dsaPublicKeyParameters);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n### Option 3 — P/Invoke to OpenSSL on macOS\nInstall OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and call it directly. This is fragile and not recommended for production.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation:** Go with **Option 2** for backward-compatible verification, and plan a migration to ECDSA/RSA long-term.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92c4d415-fe4c-4b39-a803-df51ffe90a37","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a known issue in the .NET ecosystem. Let me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Microsoft started deprecating certain cryptographic algorithms. Specifically, DSA support on macOS has been a known issue because Apple's security frameworks don't natively support DSA (they dropped it). .NET on macOS historically used OpenSSL (via a shim) for DSA operations, but Microsoft has been moving away from shipping OpenSSL dependencies.\n \nLooking at the progression more carefully, DSA was already being phased out on macOS through earlier .NET versions, with Microsoft marking these APIs as unsupported on that platform starting in .NET 9. The `DSA.Create()` method now throws an exception when called on macOS.\n\nThe underlying issue is that Apple deprecated DSA in their native security frameworks, and .NET previously worked around this by using OpenSSL through Homebrew. But as Microsoft removed that OpenSSL dependency on macOS in recent versions, algorithms like DSA that only existed through OpenSSL became unavailable, triggering the platform exception.\n\nFor workarounds, I can either use a third-party library like BouncyCastle to handle DSA operations, call OpenSSL directly through P/Invoke, or ideally migrate to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or RSA if the use case allows it. Since this is more of a conceptual question, I don't need to search for anything—the issue stems from that architectural shift in .NET's macOS crypto support around version 7 or 8.","outputTokens":1293,"requestId":"702E:21BFEE:5DF4021:65D58C0:69FBEEA2"},"id":"a629424d-cd03-4401-aa8b-8143e5795870","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:45:38.114Z","parentId":"74ab2903-ae66-44ba-9f9c-d82708f39aef"}
